<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-799-340  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 799 340.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Digital Review  Oct 23 1989 v6 n42 p61(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>U.S. government takes on hackers. (column)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Bequai, August.andM;</AUTHOR><SUMMARY>The US government is learning that computer hacking is dangerous.andO;Law enforcement officers need computer training and equipment tofight computer hackers.andP;  Regulation is an attractive if partialsolution to hacking.andP;  The FCC realizes that electronic bulletinboards are a fertile ground for hackers.andP;  Operators may berequired to get licenses.andP;  Hacking is an international issue, ashackers can prey on foreign computer systems with impunity.andO;International cooperation may be the solution for this problem.andM;</SUMMARY><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Computer HackersLaw EnforcementGovernment RegulationUnited States. Federal Communications CommissionInternationalSecurityNational GovernmentTraining of EmployeesComputer Bulletin Boards.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>U.S.andP;  Government Takes On HackersandM;Congress and the Bush administration are learning that it takes more thantalk to fight crime, whether the criminals are Colombian drug kingpins orcollegiate hackers.andM;The federal government is well aware that law enforcement agencies need moneyto battle computer-based crime effectively.andP;  But the government is alsocoming to recognize the importance of proper technological training.andM;What's turning Congress around is that bookmakers, loan sharks andorganized-crime figures are using computers to track their operations--and insome cases, to commit their crimes.andP;  Computers, which are dangerous enough inthe hands of clever undergraduates, are truly lethal weapons when wielded byprofessional criminals.andM;Plainly, law enforcement must be able to fight fire with fire.andP;  If the policehave the right training and equipment, investigating a hacking incident orcomputer-based criminal operation should become as routine as checking out aburglary.andM;As the Washington establishment reevaluates its stance, regulation seems likean attractive (if only partial) solution.andP;  If there are more regulations,hackers will find it tougher to escape the black hole of the federalbureaucracy.andM;Meanwhile, the Federal Communications Commission has set its sights onelectronic bulletin boards, often fertile ground for hackers.andP;  Not only maybulletin board operators soon have to obtain licenses, they may even have toregister their boards with the FCC, as radio and television station ownersalready do.andM;The United States isn't the only country that's worried about computer-basedcrime.andP;  National borders have become irrelevant in the age of globalnetworks.andP;  Hackers in Canada and West Germany prey on U.S.andP;  computer systemswith impunity, and Californians return the favor by hacking British systems.andM;But international concern may translate into international cooperation.andO;Great Britain's House of Commons is currently working on anti-hackinglegislation, and several Asian countries are developing regional plans forcracking down on computer-based criminal activities.andP;  Eventually, theelectronic bandits may have nowhere left to hide.andM;The U.S.andP;  and other governments are beginning to understand that hackers aredangerous: They ravage corporate and government computer systems by suckingtheir very lifeblood--information.andP;  If more people start thinking of hackersas criminals instead of cute kids or folk heroes, we might have a chance ofwinning the war on computer-based crime.andO;</TEXT></DOC>